              <h1 class="title">Finding Art</h1>
        </div>

    
    </div>
   <!-- /navigation -->

                				        <div id="content">
                    <div id="content-content" class="clear-block"> <script type="text/javascript">var re="";</script>
<div class="artwork-content">
    <div id="artwork-details">
        <div id="tombstone">
   
    <p><strong>Family Activity: Finding Art</strong><br />       <div class="content">
<p>Learn about an artwork made from found objects and construct one yourself.  Includes an art-making activity.</p><br />
<h3>Introduction:</h3>
<p>Richard Hunt's <a href="../Hero"><em>Hero Construction</em></a> was made from <a href="1034#foundobjects">found objects</a>—old pipes, bits of metal, and automobile parts. The artist discovered these materials in junkyards and on the street.</p>
<div class="image wrap">
<p><img src="../images/E16550.jpg" border="0" class="inline" /></p>
</div>
<h3>Activity</h3>
<p>Make a sculpture of your own with objects from around your house.</p>
<div class="image wrap">
<p><img src="../images/construction.jpg" border="0" class="inline" /></p>
</div>
<h3>Materials Needed:</h3>
<ul>
<li><a href="../Hero"><em>Hero Construction</em></a>'</li>
<li><a href="1034#foundobjects">found objects</a></li>
<li>Glue gun or strong tape</li>
<li>Tempera or acrylic paint</li>
<li>Paintbrush</li>
</ul>
<h3>Steps:</h3>
<ol>
<li>Spend a few days searching your home and neighborhood and collecting natural and man-made materials, such as leaves, branches, and broken toys. Be sure to ask for permission to take objects that are not yours! Fill a grocery bag with these materials until you have a good collection.</li>
<li>With adult supervision, construct a sculpture from these objects using a glue gun or tape. Think about how you can use your materials to make a human, <a href="1034#abstract">abstract</a>, or machine-like form. If your <a href="1034#construction">construction</a> cannot stand on its own, glue it to a cardboard or wood support.</li>
<li>If you’d like, paint the final sculpture to give it a <a href="1034#patina">patina</a> like <a href="1034#castsculpture">cast sculpture.</a> </li>
</ol><br />
<h3>Glossary</h3>
<p><strong><a name="abstract" id="abstract"></a>abstract</strong> (<em>adj</em>)<br />
not recognizable; comprised of expressive color, form, and texture</p>
<p><strong><a name="castsculpture" id="castsculpture"></a>cast sculpture</strong> (<em>n</em>)<br />
a work of art made by pouring melted liquid, such as bronze, into a mold and then letting it harden. The mold is often constructed from
a clay, plaster, or wax model.</p>
<p><strong><a name="construction" id="construction"></a>construction</strong> (<em>n</em>)<br />
an assembly (usually three-dimensional) of diverse materials, such as found objects</p>
<p><strong><a name="foundobjects" id="foundobjects"></a>found objects</strong> (<em>n</em>, pl)<br />
materials that were once used for other purposes and later found by an artist and incorporated into a work of art</p>
<p><strong><a name="patina" id="patina"></a>patina</strong> (<em>n</em>)<br />
a crust or film that appears gradually (as a result of chemical reactions) or is placed deliberately on the surface of a sculpture</p>

</div><br /><br />
    	 Art Access<br />    	    </p>

    </div><!--/tombstone-->
    </div><!--/artwork-details-->
